		<header>
			
			<h1>Ambitious plans for Jamaican sugar sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 June 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The Jamaican Minister of Agriculture believes that local sugar cane production can be increased from 1.3m tonnes in 2010 ‘closer to 3.5 million tonnes’ ‘over the next two to three years’, according to reports in the Jamaican press. According to the reports, the government ‘plans to spend $3 billion [€24.9m] over the next three years to more than triple sugar cane production across the island’. Agriculture Minister Christopher Tufton announced that the government also intends to facilitate private investment in ‘a sugar refinery with a 200,000-tonne capacity, to supply both the local and regional markets where there is a 300,000-tonne demand for refined sugar’. Molasses production was also seen as an important revenue spinner, with further scope for sugar cane to play ‘a critical role in the country’s renewable energy policy’. However, the minister also recognised that ‘if the industry is to maximise its earning potential, there has to be a massive injection of capital to modernise the estates.’ The Jamaican sugar industry is currently projected to produce some 157,000 tonnes of sugar in 2011 compared to 126,000 tonnes last season.</p><p>The Jamaican government is hoping that much of the investment for this sugar-industry renewal will come from the Chinese company Complant, which has agreed to take over ‘the assets of the Frome, Bernard Lodge and Monymusk estates for US$9 million’. As part of the agreement, Complant will ‘invest US$127 million in the refurbishing of field and factory operations on the estates’ and, if a feasibility study proves favourable, a further US$200 million will be invested in a sugar refinery at Frome. An announcement on the future of the refinery project is expected ‘by August’ 2011.</p><p>Minister Tufton described the Frome refinery project as ‘the largest single investment of all times in the agricultural sector’ and ‘a profound vote of confidence in the Jamaican economy’. Speaking in April, Complant’s chairman Li Zhimin told reporters that the company ‘plans to upgrade the annual production capacity of Frome and Monymusk estates to 170,000 tonnes of sugar’ and initiate ethanol production. He called for all staff to ‘change the old mindset’, stressing that the active engagement of all stakeholders was essential to the future of the sector. The Chinese company will provide ‘only senior managers and key technical experts’ for the estates and associated industrial operations, but will leave day-to-day operations to Jamaican staff.</p>
		
		
